            Dr. Sen earned a PhD in civil engineering from the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign in December 2019, where he studied the effect of construction materials (primarily pavement materials) on the urban heat island effect using Computational Fluid Dynamics. He has been working as a postdoctoral associate at Pitt since January 2020, where he has worked on efficiently modeling crack development in concrete pavements and implementing a new faulting model into Pitt’s BCOA-ME online tool. He participates in activities of the TRB AKP00(2) Subcommittee on Sustainable and Resilient Pavements and serves as a peer reviewer for several well-known journals in pavement engineering and environmental modeling.  

